from typing import List

class Solution:
    def minimizeConcatenatedLength(self, words: List[str]) -> int:
        from functools import cache

        @cache
        def dp(i, left, right):
            if i == len(words):
                return 0

            word = words[i]
            # Option 1: Append word to the current string
            append_length = dp(i + 1, left, word[-1]) + len(word)
            if word[0] == right:
                append_length -= 1

            # Option 2: Prepend word to the current string
            prepend_length = dp(i + 1, word[0], right) + len(word)
            if word[-1] == left:
                prepend_length -= 1

            return min(append_length, prepend_length)

        return dp(1, words[0][0], words[0][-1]) + len(words[0])
```

This solution uses dynamic programming with memoization to explore all possible ways to concatenate the words while keeping track of the first and last characters of the resulting string. The `dp` function calculates the minimum length of the concatenated string starting from the `i`-th word, given the first character `left` and the last character `right` of the current concatenated string. The function considers both appending and prepending the current word to the concatenated string and chooses the option that results in the minimum length. The base case is when all words have been processed (`i == len(words)`), in which case the length is 0. The final result is obtained by calling `dp` with the initial word and its first and last characters.
